[6
Date: 28 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sunday Times 28 Oct 2001 [edited
<http://www.sunday-times.co.uk:80/>

Little red 'bites' were the first sign that I was victim
---------------------------------------------------------------
Claire Fletcher, a Briton working for CBS News in New York, recounts
how she discovered that she had anthrax
"...we heard about the first case of anthrax at another television
network. That was when I started to worry about two pimples on my left
cheek. I had first noticed them around 1 Oct [2001, when I thought
the tiny red marks were insect bites. But overnight they blistered and
turned blackish and my cheek swelled. I thought I might have developed
an allergic reaction to the bites and called my doctor, who prescribed
penicillin.
I never felt any illness, weakness or nausea. I continued to follow a
work-out regime at the gym and carried on with my training for the New
York City marathon, which I will be running next week. It never
occurred to me that I might have anthrax.
By the time news of the NBC case broke, the bug bites looked more like
a lesion. I thought perhaps I should get a second opinion. A friend at
CBS made an appointment with one of New York's top dermatologists. I
also got in touch with a doctor from the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta, who referred me to a colleague in New York.
She prescribed a dose of the antibiotic Cipro 'just to be safe'. "
--
